1
00:00:35,568 --> 00:00:37,365
Where does it come from?

2
00:00:37,437 --> 00:00:41,771
This quest, this need
to solve life's mysteries,

3
00:00:41,841 --> 00:00:44,901
when the simplest of questions
can never be answered?

4
00:00:47,414 --> 00:00:51,817
Why are we here? What is the soul?
Why do we dream?

5
00:00:54,287 --> 00:00:57,279
Perhaps we'd be better off
not looking at all.

6
00:00:57,357 --> 00:00:59,188
Not delving, not yearning.

7
00:01:01,528 --> 00:01:05,464
That's not human nature.
Not the human heart.

8
00:01:07,434 --> 00:01:10,232
That is not why we are here.

9
00:01:34,060 --> 00:01:35,357
How's he doing?

10
00:01:37,931 --> 00:01:39,922
- I'm sorry. Did I scare you?
- No.

11
00:01:41,367 --> 00:01:43,733
No, I just... I keep having
these amazing dreams

12
00:01:43,803 --> 00:01:46,101
every time I close my eyes and...

13
00:01:46,639 --> 00:01:47,765
...never mind.

14
00:01:49,976 --> 00:01:52,342
He likes me to read him the stock page.

15
00:01:52,579 --> 00:01:54,137
Has he been conscious at all?

16
00:01:54,214 --> 00:01:55,340
No.

17
00:01:56,316 --> 00:01:58,910
Been a week now. I think he's close.

18
00:01:59,619 --> 00:02:01,348
A couple more days, maybe.

19
00:02:04,023 --> 00:02:05,047

20
00:02:05,125 --> 00:02:07,719
You know I don't know
what he'd do without you.

21
00:02:07,794 --> 00:02:09,989
- You got a real gift.
- Just doing my job.

22
00:02:10,063 --> 00:02:12,725
No, you're like a son to him.

23
00:02:13,266 --> 00:02:15,325
No, that would make us
like brother and sister.

24
00:02:15,401 --> 00:02:16,698
Might be... might be a little awkward

25
00:02:16,769 --> 00:02:19,203
if I ever wanted to ask you out.

26
00:02:22,342 --> 00:02:25,140
I'm sorry, that was...
That was inappropriate.

27
00:02:25,211 --> 00:02:27,338
No, it's sweet, it's...

28
00:02:27,413 --> 00:02:29,472
I'm dating somebody.

29
00:02:29,549 --> 00:02:31,847
Yeah. No, really, it's OK.

30
00:02:35,755 --> 00:02:37,450
I need to change his IV.

31
00:02:38,224 --> 00:02:39,748
I'm sorry, of course.

32
00:02:44,330 --> 00:02:47,265
Man is a narcissistic species by nature.

33
00:02:47,734 --> 00:02:51,135
We have colonized the four corners
of our tiny planet.

34
00:02:51,204 --> 00:02:54,298
But we are not the pinnacle
of so-called evolution.

35
00:02:54,674 --> 00:02:57,609
That honor belongs to the lowly cockroach.

36
00:02:58,278 --> 00:03:02,271
They say that man uses only
a tenth of his brain power.

37
00:03:02,582 --> 00:03:06,712
Another percent and we might actually
be worthy of God's image.

38
00:03:07,887 --> 00:03:10,822
Unless, of course,
that day has already arrived.

39
00:03:11,191 --> 00:03:14,649
The Human Genome Project
has discovered that tiny variations

40
00:03:14,727 --> 00:03:19,562
in man's genetic code are taking place
at increasingly rapid rates.

41
00:03:19,966 --> 00:03:23,424
Teleportation, levitation,
tissue regeneration.

42
00:03:23,503 --> 00:03:25,801
Is this outside the realm of possibility?

43
00:03:25,872 --> 00:03:29,171
Or is man entering a new gateway to evolution?

44
00:03:29,242 --> 00:03:33,702
Is he finally standing at the threshold
to true human potential?

45
00:03:36,916 --> 00:03:38,907
I'm sorry. I'm out of time.

46
00:03:44,824 --> 00:03:48,225
I know, I know, I'm beginning to sound
like my father. I can't help it.

47
00:03:48,294 --> 00:03:50,626
You know, they can fire me
too, if they like,

48
00:03:50,697 --> 00:03:54,155
but there is something to it,
Nirad. As crazy as it sounds.

49
00:03:56,869 --> 00:03:58,029
What is it?

50
00:03:58,104 --> 00:03:59,696
It's your father.

51
00:04:00,640 --> 00:04:02,039
He's dead.

52
00:04:05,712 --> 00:04:06,906
How?

53
00:04:06,980 --> 00:04:09,710
Driving a taxi in New York City
is a very dangerous job.

54
00:04:09,782 --> 00:04:11,181
The wrong fare, the wrong time.

55
00:04:11,251 --> 00:04:12,809
We may never know what really happened.

56
00:04:12,885 --> 00:04:14,580
No, I spoke to him two days ago.

57
00:04:14,654 --> 00:04:17,646
He was convinced someone was following
him, trying to steal his research.

58
00:04:17,724 --> 00:04:18,884
He died because of his theories.

59
00:04:18,958 --> 00:04:20,550
- That's crazy.
- Is it?

60
00:04:21,394 --> 00:04:23,021
The man left his family,

61
00:04:23,096 --> 00:04:26,259
discredited his career, to chase wild
theories halfway around the world.

62
00:04:26,332 --> 00:04:27,390
Where are you going?

63
00:04:27,467 --> 00:04:30,129
To his apartment, to get his papers,
his research.

64
00:04:30,203 --> 00:04:32,330
He was this close
to finding the first of them.

65
00:04:32,405 --> 00:04:34,999
His Patient Zero, he tracked him
to Queens, New York.

66
00:04:35,074 --> 00:04:36,803
Mohinder, listen to me.

67
00:04:36,876 --> 00:04:39,037
Your father was my
colleague and my friend.

68
00:04:39,112 --> 00:04:41,740
A respected professor,
a brilliant geneticist.

69
00:04:41,814 --> 00:04:43,805
But he had clearly
lost touch with reality.

70
00:04:43,883 --> 00:04:45,441
I've followed in his footsteps.

71
00:04:45,518 --> 00:04:47,076
My thesis is based on his research.

72
00:04:47,153 --> 00:04:48,814
Yes, you always wanted his approval.

73
00:04:48,888 --> 00:04:50,947
And now you're telling me
that it was all for nothing.

74
00:04:51,024 --> 00:04:53,219
I'm telling you to let go.

75
00:04:53,293 --> 00:04:57,286
I need to know why he died. I need to
know that it wasn't all for nothing.

76
00:04:58,164 --> 00:05:00,826
And then I need to finish
what he started.

77
00:05:59,325 --> 00:06:00,792

78
00:06:02,962 --> 00:06:04,088
Hello?

79
00:06:05,164 --> 00:06:07,632
Yeah, yeah, I'm at his place now.

80
00:06:08,468 --> 00:06:11,528
No, no, no, he left everything behind
but his computer.

81
00:06:11,771 --> 00:06:13,966
Research, the map.

82
00:06:14,040 --> 00:06:16,941
Yeah, let's get a team in here
to bag and tag everything.

83
00:06:17,009 --> 00:06:18,306

84
00:06:18,378 --> 00:06:19,868
I gotta call you right back.

85
00:06:46,005 --> 00:06:48,064

86
00:07:20,807 --> 00:07:22,502

87
00:07:49,769 --> 00:07:50,895
Pervert!

88
00:08:14,861 --> 00:08:16,522
Time to get up, Micah.

89
00:08:20,066 --> 00:08:21,658
Micah.

90
00:08:26,839 --> 00:08:28,466
Micah!

91
00:08:29,108 --> 00:08:31,702
Micah. Micah.

92
00:08:31,777 --> 00:08:32,869
What?

93
00:08:33,312 --> 00:08:34,779
Damn it, Micah, don't do that to me.

94
00:08:34,847 --> 00:08:36,109
Do what?

95
00:08:36,182 --> 00:08:38,946
Just you need to be
careful. All right?

96
00:08:40,419 --> 00:08:43,320
And I don't want you talking to
any strangers, do you understand?

97
00:08:43,389 --> 00:08:45,414
I'm just working on my computer.

98
00:08:45,791 --> 00:08:49,124
The logic board was bad,
so I had to build a new one.

99
00:08:50,129 --> 00:08:51,391
A new one...

100
00:08:52,732 --> 00:08:55,860
Did anyone ever tell you you're the
smartest little man on the planet?

101
00:08:55,935 --> 00:08:57,926
You do. All the time.

102
00:09:01,941 --> 00:09:03,101
What's this?

103
00:09:03,809 --> 00:09:07,006
It's a pinhole camera. It's for the eclipse.

104
00:09:08,414 --> 00:09:10,405
The moon's gonna cover up the sun today.

105
00:09:10,483 --> 00:09:11,677
We're supposed to look at it at school.

106
00:09:11,751 --> 00:09:16,518
Speaking of which, you need to go
get ready. Can't be late. Not today.

107
00:09:16,656 --> 00:09:19,352
Mom, I'm already dressed
and I've packed my own lunch.

108
00:09:19,425 --> 00:09:21,325
That's what I've been doing this morning.

109
00:09:21,394 --> 00:09:22,452
What about you?

110
00:09:22,528 --> 00:09:24,428
Hey, don't get smart with me.

111
00:09:24,664 --> 00:09:26,529
All right, I've been working to pay our bills.

112
00:09:26,599 --> 00:09:28,464
Yeah, that's why they turned off our gas again?

113
00:09:28,534 --> 00:09:30,126


114
00:09:30,536 --> 00:09:32,595
Go grab your stuff and
wait by the back door, OK?

115
00:09:32,672 --> 00:09:34,606
- Why?
- Just do it.

116
00:09:43,683 --> 00:09:44,809
Mom, what's going on?

117
00:09:44,884 --> 00:09:47,409
Never mind, just keep your voice down
and stay close to me.

118
00:09:47,486 --> 00:09:48,817

119
00:09:52,391 --> 00:09:54,086

120
00:10:15,181 --> 00:10:16,773
Camera ready?

121
00:10:16,849 --> 00:10:18,714
Yeah, almost! Hold on.

122
00:10:18,918 --> 00:10:22,513
This looks like 70, 80 feet.
This is so unreal.

123
00:10:22,588 --> 00:10:23,885
OK, I'm good!

124
00:10:25,124 --> 00:10:26,523
OK. Oh my...

125
00:10:26,592 --> 00:10:27,854

126
00:10:28,294 --> 00:10:30,819
Oh, my God.
Oh, my God. Claire?

127
00:10:31,864 --> 00:10:33,058
Oh, my God.

128
00:10:33,165 --> 00:10:34,564

129
00:10:37,136 --> 00:10:38,330
Claire!

130
00:10:52,551 --> 00:10:56,612
This is Claire Bennet and
that was attempt number six.

131
00:11:30,423 --> 00:11:31,981
You get out here, yes?

132
00:11:32,058 --> 00:11:33,992
Yes, sorry. Thanks.

133
00:11:38,164 --> 00:11:40,496
Mr. Linderman, I'm gonna have to call
you back in five minutes, OK?

134
00:11:40,566 --> 00:11:41,590
Thank you.

135
00:11:41,667 --> 00:11:44,067
I'm late. I've got a fundraiser and a
drinks meeting. What is it?

136
00:11:44,136 --> 00:11:48,004
It happened two more times. Sometimes
I'm falling, sometimes I'm flying.

137
00:11:48,074 --> 00:11:50,201
- Sometimes you're in 'em.
- I don't have time for this now.

138
00:11:50,276 --> 00:11:52,039
They're not just dreams, Nathan.

139
00:11:52,111 --> 00:11:53,271
Hold this.

140
00:11:53,345 --> 00:11:54,607
I thought they'd go away, but they're not.

141
00:11:54,680 --> 00:11:56,477
Jim, I need this back by 6:00, please. Thanks.

142
00:11:56,549 --> 00:11:59,416
This morning when I got out of bed, my
foot hovered before it hit the ground.

143
00:11:59,485 --> 00:12:00,918
Hovered. For a split second,

144
00:12:00,986 --> 00:12:02,851
like I was... like I was floating.

145
00:12:03,289 --> 00:12:05,883
I'm telling you, I think I can fly.

146
00:12:08,160 --> 00:12:09,957
- These all are "Undecideds"?
- Mmm-hmm.

147
00:12:10,362 --> 00:12:11,420
Tell you what, you think you can fly?

148
00:12:11,497 --> 00:12:14,227
Why don't you jump off the Brooklyn Bridge?
See what happens.

149
00:12:14,300 --> 00:12:16,700
Maybe I ought to start with something
a little lower first.

150
00:12:16,769 --> 00:12:18,703
- Just like learning to walk.
- You're serious.

151
00:12:18,771 --> 00:12:19,795
Oh, I'm serious.

152
00:12:19,872 --> 00:12:21,669
You need to snap out of it, Peter.

153
00:12:21,741 --> 00:12:23,766
Go see a doctor, get some drugs.

154
00:12:24,009 --> 00:12:25,909
But do not pull a Roger Clinton
on me man,

155
00:12:25,978 --> 00:12:27,275
I'm eight points down in the polls.

156
00:12:27,346 --> 00:12:29,143
Look, this isn't about you, all right?

157
00:12:29,215 --> 00:12:31,547
Look, something is happening to me,
and I have this feeling

158
00:12:31,617 --> 00:12:33,482
that you're the only person
that's gonna understand this.

159
00:12:33,552 --> 00:12:35,747
Why the hell would I understand that
you think you can fly?

160
00:12:35,821 --> 00:12:38,187
Because you're my brother!

161
00:12:40,025 --> 00:12:42,391
Mom, look, I can't talk right now. I've got...

162
00:12:42,461 --> 00:12:43,450
What?

163
00:12:43,596 --> 00:12:45,223
I'll be there in 10 minutes.

164
00:12:45,297 --> 00:12:46,992
What'd she do now?

165
00:12:48,467 --> 00:12:50,458
- She got arrested.
- Arrested for what?

166
00:12:50,536 --> 00:12:51,696
Shoplifting.

167
00:12:53,572 --> 00:12:55,301
I'm so depressed.

168
00:12:55,908 --> 00:12:58,206
What? What are you talking about? Why?

169
00:13:00,713 --> 00:13:04,205
I mean, I mean, besides the fact that it
was so gross that I almost fudged myself,

170
00:13:04,283 --> 00:13:07,775
this is the single coolest thing to happen
to this town in like, 100 years.

171
00:13:07,853 --> 00:13:10,287
Not if nobody finds out, it's not.

172
00:13:11,657 --> 00:13:13,124
Why'd you want me to tape it?

173
00:13:13,192 --> 00:13:14,750
I have my reasons.

174
00:13:16,295 --> 00:13:18,456
I still can't believe you asked me.

175
00:13:18,631 --> 00:13:21,657
You stopped talking to me
in like, 6th grade.

176
00:13:22,268 --> 00:13:23,929
It's safer this way.

177
00:13:24,904 --> 00:13:26,496
Why? 'Cause I'm not popular,

178
00:13:26,572 --> 00:13:29,939
so no one would believe me even
if I did tell? Which I won't.

179
00:13:30,543 --> 00:13:32,010
Something like that.

180
00:13:33,579 --> 00:13:36,742
It's not like you're not gonna be
popular anymore.

181
00:13:36,816 --> 00:13:37,805
Popular?

182
00:13:38,551 --> 00:13:40,644
Who said anything about being popular?

183
00:13:40,719 --> 00:13:42,914
My life as I know it is over, OK?

184
00:13:42,988 --> 00:13:46,048
I've got the Bishop game
next week, SAT's in October,

185
00:13:46,125 --> 00:13:47,888
homecoming's three weeks from today,
and I'm a freak show.

186
00:13:47,960 --> 00:13:49,757
You're being a little
dramatic, don't you think?

187
00:13:49,829 --> 00:13:51,854
No, I don't think.

188
00:13:51,964 --> 00:13:54,524
I have busted, like, every bone in my body,

189
00:13:54,600 --> 00:13:58,001
stabbed myself in the chest, I've shoved
a two-foot steel rod through my neck,

190
00:13:58,070 --> 00:14:00,197
and I don't have a scratch on me.

191
00:14:00,272 --> 00:14:02,740
What do you call that thing sticking out?

192
00:14:05,044 --> 00:14:06,739
Great.

193
00:14:12,384 --> 00:14:15,444
- Just give me the tape, OK?
- Sure.

194
00:14:22,161 --> 00:14:24,721
I can give you a ride on my handlebars...

195
00:14:25,865 --> 00:14:26,854
...if you want.

196
00:14:28,334 --> 00:14:30,199
That's OK, I'll walk.

197
00:14:32,304 --> 00:14:33,601

198
00:14:34,506 --> 00:14:37,134
Look, thanks, OK?

199
00:14:37,476 --> 00:14:41,003
I'll talk to you in front of people
at school tomorrow.

200
00:14:41,380 --> 00:14:42,608
Promise.

201
00:14:43,616 --> 00:14:45,413

202
00:15:04,837 --> 00:15:06,202

203
00:15:42,942 --> 00:15:45,001
- What do we have?
- Three clear.

204
00:15:45,077 --> 00:15:47,011
- Give me a count.
- All clear.

205
00:15:49,315 --> 00:15:50,612

206
00:15:50,683 --> 00:15:52,981
How the hell did they know we were coming?

207
00:15:53,319 --> 00:15:56,152
Railroad schedules from the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission.

208
00:15:56,221 --> 00:16:00,157
Routes for transporting
nuclear material. Right.

209
00:16:00,225 --> 00:16:03,854
Not much else. Couple of notes here,
mostly Arabic.

210
00:16:04,063 --> 00:16:05,428
Except for this.

211
00:16:06,799 --> 00:16:09,324
"Odessa." What the hell
is this, a name?

212
00:16:09,401 --> 00:16:12,666
Oh, it's a town in Texas. Odessa.

213
00:16:13,639 --> 00:16:14,867
What's that?

214
00:16:15,708 --> 00:16:19,610
You asked me what Odessa is. It's a town
in Texas. And a city in Russia, I think.

215
00:16:19,678 --> 00:16:21,475
What are you talking about?

216
00:16:22,381 --> 00:16:23,939

217
00:16:33,625 --> 00:16:36,116
What do you think? CIA or FBI?

218
00:16:36,195 --> 00:16:38,561
No, she's dressed too nice for FBI.

219
00:16:39,064 --> 00:16:41,965
Saw the test scores got posted this morning.

220
00:16:42,368 --> 00:16:44,996
Don't worry about it, man.
Not everybody's a test-taker.

221
00:16:45,404 --> 00:16:47,702
Who wants to be on SWAT anyway?

222
00:16:48,173 --> 00:16:49,470
Too dangerous.

223
00:16:50,876 --> 00:16:53,709

224
00:16:59,451 --> 00:17:00,440

225
00:17:04,356 --> 00:17:05,789
You all right, man?

226
00:17:29,014 --> 00:17:30,345
What're you doing here, son?

227
00:17:30,682 --> 00:17:33,173
You're not authorized to be in here.
Wait a minute.

228
00:17:33,252 --> 00:17:34,241
Shh!

229
00:17:45,831 --> 00:17:47,958
Don't shoot. Don't... Don't shoot!

230
00:17:51,737 --> 00:17:55,298
Now, the train is registered to the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission.

231
00:17:55,374 --> 00:17:59,504
And there has been no official statement,
yet, as to what was in the car.

232
00:17:59,578 --> 00:18:02,274
But judging by the amount
of security around here,

233
00:18:02,347 --> 00:18:05,839
it's pretty clear it was
something very valuable.

234
00:18:08,387 --> 00:18:11,652
Reporting live from Odessa, Texas,
I'm Laura Lancaster.

235
00:18:24,403 --> 00:18:25,392

236
00:18:38,684 --> 00:18:39,673

237
00:19:01,740 --> 00:19:03,799
I want a lawyer.

238
00:19:03,876 --> 00:19:06,276
You lead me to the rest of your cell,
I'll think about it.

239
00:19:06,345 --> 00:19:07,835
Until then, no one knows you're here,

240
00:19:07,913 --> 00:19:10,711
which means no one will know if you're not.

241
00:19:11,216 --> 00:19:15,175
You found him, didn't you?
You found the engineer.

242
00:19:15,320 --> 00:19:18,983
He's here in LA.
Where is he?

243
00:19:19,491 --> 00:19:20,788
Where is he?

244
00:19:28,066 --> 00:19:31,035
This is LAPD jurisdiction.
We need to take him into custody.

245
00:19:31,103 --> 00:19:33,503
He stays here till I tell you he leaves.

246
00:19:34,273 --> 00:19:35,763
Who's the engineer?

247
00:19:35,841 --> 00:19:37,365
Amid Halebi.

248
00:19:37,442 --> 00:19:40,673
Saudi national with a PhD
in Nuclear Physics.

249
00:19:41,246 --> 00:19:44,738
Was 20th terrorist on 9/11, until
he didn't show up for the main event.

250
00:19:44,816 --> 00:19:47,717
Turns out, he fell for an American girl
he'd met a few months earlier.

251
00:19:47,786 --> 00:19:50,380
September 10th, 2001,
he went off the grid.

252
00:19:50,622 --> 00:19:52,886
And they tracked him here?

253
00:19:52,991 --> 00:19:54,288
He brought the girl back to bury her.

254
00:19:54,359 --> 00:19:57,123
She died of cancer. Funeral was yesterday.

255
00:19:57,196 --> 00:19:58,788
He's back on the grid.

256
00:19:59,531 --> 00:20:01,658
Let's see if the Amazing
Karnack here has some answers.

257
00:20:01,733 --> 00:20:02,791
Who is he?

258
00:20:02,868 --> 00:20:05,234
Matthew Parkman. He's eight
years on the force,

259
00:20:05,304 --> 00:20:09,070
